l of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":89,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Waller was born in 1460, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1555, in Dorking, Surrey, England, at the age of 95."},"et":{"1460–1555":"1460–1555","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1555":"1555","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","